==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Supersede
<hw>Su`per*sede"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Superseded</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Superseding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>supersedere</ets>, <ets>supersessum</ets>, to sit above, be
superior to, forbear, omit; <ets>super</ets> above + <ets>sedere</ets>
to sit: cf. F. <ets>supers⟦eacute⟧der</ets>. See <er>Sit</er>, and cf.
<er>Surcease</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To come, or be placed, in the
room of; to replace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To displace, or set aside, and put another in place
of; <as>as, to <ex>supersede</ex> an officer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make void, inefficacious, or useless, by superior
power, or by coming in the place of; to set aside; to render
unnecessary; to suspend; to stay.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing is supposed that can <qex>supersede</qex> the known laws
of natural motion.</q> <rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Old Law)</fld> <def>To omit; to forbear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Supersedeas</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
